Hey, my team is planning to do a new robot for the off-season (2910), we are in advanced cad and we are almost finished. But there is a part that my team wants to manufacture that I‚Äôm pretty sure isn‚Äôt possible to manufacture with our resources and even if it‚Äôs possible it will take an unbearable amount of time and energy and it will be a complete waste.
I will be happy if someone can give us advice about this part and tell if it‚Äôs even possible to manufacture.

Here are some informations about the part and our resources:
‚óèour cnc is Laguna CNC
‚óèthe aluminum we will use for this part is 6061
‚óèwe have ‚Öõinch, 4mm, 6mm heads for the cnc
‚óèthe part will be made from a 35mm aluminum plate
‚óèwe have special clamps to hold in a good position the plate in the different stages of the manufacturing

Um. May I suspect the designer is a 3D printing enthusiast?

Fixturing is going to be quite a challenge. I think you need to cut into all six faces.

On a router you will need to start with "make a fixture that can repeatably orient and secure your part in all required orientations ". That would likely be easier on a mill‚Ä¶ but still do-able on a stiff router.

You should take a quick peek at Patrick‚Äôs video on making crazy parts for the SDS MK5.

The depth of cut on many features looks deep relative to the feature size. That central hole needs a bigger end mill. Carbide for sure, otherwise flexibility will kill your work‚Ä¶
